  ('en', 'Céramique et poterie', 'The ceramics of which civilization is universally known for porcelain ?', 'Chinese', 'Greek', 'French', 'Peruvian', '1', 'The large blue and white vases, which appeared during the Yuan Mongol dynasty, will develop fully under the Ming.', ''),
  ('en', 'Céramique et poterie', 'In pottery, what technique of formatting uses only the fingers ?', 'Modeling', 'Shooting', 'Pouring', 'Trying', '1', 'For cooking, the different pieces obtained are placed in a oven at a temperature of 1,000 ° C for about eight hours.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pottery'),
  ('en', 'Céramique et poterie', 'Which pre-Inca civilization is best known for ceramics ?', 'Nazca', 'Patayan', 'Pipils', 'Valdivia', '2', 'Little colorful during the initial period, they are of great polychrome richness later, between medium and late Nazca.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazca_culture'),
  ('en', 'Céramique et poterie', 'What object is used to cover floors, walls and showers ?', 'Tile', 'Bunker', 'Lintel', 'Friesland', '1', 'Tiles are used to form the wall of wall paintings and floor coverings, from simple squares to complex mosaics.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tile'),
  ('en', 'Céramique et poterie', 'What kind of ceramics are part of the grapes and porcelain ?', 'Vitrified', 'Porous', 'Stannifer', 'Fine', '2', 'Le grés is a ceramic material characterized by a very great hardness and excellent resistance to chemical attack.', ''),
  ('en', 'Céramique et poterie', 'Which ceramic material is baked at a temperature above 1200 ° C ?', 'Grès', 'Patina', 'Colombin', 'Porcelain', '2', 'The grape appeared in China during the Shang Dynasty and the Han Dynasty, reaching its perfection with Song\'s sausages.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stoneware'),
  ('en', 'Céramique et poterie', 'Which museum offers a magnificent collection of 340,000 pieces of ceramics ?', 'Forbidden City', 'Louvre', 'Tate Museum', 'Vatican', '2', 'The Palace Museum at the Forbidden City of Beijing features Chinese imperial collections from the Tang and Song dynasties.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forbidden_City'),
  ('en', 'Céramique et poterie', 'Which of these terms is directly opposed to that of terracotta ?', 'Raw earth', 'Clay', 'Old Earth', 'Chemical Earth', '1', 'Previously to the terracotta, we find in all civilizations a pottery and bricks made of mud.', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mudbrick'),
